%N A394366 Longest sides z of integer-sided triangles (x <= y <= z) having at least one integral median and such that every integral median m satisfies gcd(x, y, z, m) = 1, ordered by increasing z, then y, then x.
%C A394366 Primitive cases only: gcd(x, y, z, m) = 1. All others arise by scaling a primitive triangle by an integer k > 1.
%C A394366 The middle and shortest sides are in A394367 and A394368, respectively. The corresponding median values m are in A394369.
%C A394366 A triangle (x <= y <= z) is included if there exists a median with integer length m = sqrt(2*y^2 + 2*z^2 - x^2)/2 (or cyclically at y or z), and every integral median m satisfies gcd(x, y, z, m) = 1.
%C A394366 From the parity condition in 4*m^2 = 2*y^2 + 2*z^2 - x^2 it follows that any side whose median is integral must be even. Thus the median divides the triangle into two integer-sided triangles. If medians to two distinct sides were integral, then x, y, z would all be even; under the gcd condition this leads to infinite 2-adic descent unless the two medians coincide. Hence at most one distinct integral median length can occur (in the isosceles case two medians may exist geometrically, but they are equal).
%H A394366 Felix Huber, <a href="/A394366/b394366.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10098</a>
%H A394366 Felix Huber, <a href="/A394366/a394366.txt">Maple program</a>
%H A394366 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/TriangleMedian.html">Triangle Median</a>
%e A394366 6 is a term because in the triangle (x, y, z) = (5, 5, 6) the median to z = 6 has length m = 4. It splits z into 3 and 3, yielding two congruent triangles (3, 4, 5), and gcd(5, 5, 6, 4) = 1.
%e A394366 9 is a term because in the triangle (x, y, z) = (7, 8, 9) the median to y = 8 has length m = 7. It splits y into 4 and 4, yielding triangles (4, 7, 7) and (4, 7, 9), and gcd(7, 8, 9, 7) = 1.
%e A394366 14 is a term because in the triangle (x, y, z) = (8, 14, 14) the medians to y = 14 and z = 14 both have length m = 9. Each splits the side into 7 and 7, yielding triangles (7, 8, 9) and (7, 9, 14)., and gcd(8, 14, 14, 9) = 1.
%p A394366 # See Huber link.
